.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Public \- Bitcoin public keys
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Public;
\&
\&        $pub = Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Public\->from_serialized([hex => $asn_hex]);
\&
\&        # verify signature of custom message
\&        # (it has to be byte string, see perlpacktut)
\&
\&        $pub\->verify_message(\*(AqHello world\*(Aq, $sig);
\&
\&        # getting address from public key (p2wpkh)
\&
\&        my $address = $pub\->get_segwit_address();
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class allows you to create a public key instance.
.PP
You can use a public key to verify messages and get addresses.
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
\fIcompressed\fR
.IX Subsection "compressed"
.PP
Boolean value indicating if this ECC key should be compressed. Default: \f(CW\*(C`true\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_compressed\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fInetwork\fR
.IX Subsection "network"
.PP
Instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Network \- current network for this key. Can be
coerced from network id. Default: current default network.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_network\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIpurpose\fR
.IX Subsection "purpose"
.PP
BIP44 purpose which was used to obtain this key. Filled automatically when
deriving an extended key. If the key was not obtained through BIP44 derivation,
this attribute is \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_purpose\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIclearer:\fR \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fItaproot_output\fR
.IX Subsection "taproot_output"
.PP
Boolean value indicating if this key was obtained through taproot tweaking or
should be used with Schnorr signatures. Default: \f(CW\*(C`false\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_taproot_output\*(C'\fR
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
Constructor is reserved for internal and advanced use only. Use "from_serialized"
instead.
.PP
\fIfrom_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "from_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $key_object = $class\->from_serialized($serialized)
.Ve
.PP
This creates a new key from string data. Argument \f(CW$serialized\fR is a
formatable bytestring which must represent a public key in ASN X9.62 format.
.PP
Returns a new key object instance.
.PP
\fIto_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "to_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $serialized = $key_object\->to_serialized()
.Ve
.PP
This returns a public key in ASN X9.62 format. The result is a bytestring which
can be further formated with \f(CW\*(C`to_format\*(C'\fR utility.
.PP
The result will vary depending on compression state: see "compressed"
.PP
\fIget_hash\fR
.IX Subsection "get_hash"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bytestr = $object\->get_hash()
.Ve
.PP
Returns hash160 of the serialized public key.
.PP
\fIwitness_program\fR
.IX Subsection "witness_program"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $script = $object\->witness_program($version, \e%args = {})
.Ve
.PP
Builds a witness program for given witness \f(CW$version\fR as
Bitcoin::Crypto::Script instance. \f(CW%args\fR depends on witness version:
.IP \(bu 4
For witness version 0 (segwit), no arguments are used.
.IP \(bu 4
For witness version 1 (taproot), \f(CW\*(C`tweak_suffix\*(C'\fR optional bytestring argument
can be passed.
.PP
\fIget_taproot_output_key\fR
.IX Subsection "get_taproot_output_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $pub = $object\->get_taproot_output_key($tweak_suffix = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Returns a new public key instance that represents an output taproot key, or
this key if it is marked as "taproot_output". Optional \f(CW$tweak_suffix\fR can
be passed as bytestring.
.PP
\fIget_xonly_key\fR
.IX Subsection "get_xonly_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $bytestring = $object\->get_xonly_key()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a 32\-byte bytestring containing the xonly key for this public key.
.PP
\fIverify_message\fR
.IX Subsection "verify_message"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $signature_valid = $object\->verify_message($message, $signature, %params)
.Ve
.PP
Verifies \f(CW$signature\fR against digest of \f(CW$message\fR (digesting it with double
sha256) using public key.
.PP
\&\f(CW%params\fR can be any of:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`flags\*(C'\fR
.Sp
An instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags. If not passed, full set
of consensus flags will be assumed (same as calling
"new" in Bitcoin::Crypto::Transaction::Flags with no arguments).
.PP
Returns boolean.
.PP
Character encoding note: \f(CW$message\fR should be encoded in the proper encoding
before passing it to this method. Passing Unicode string will cause the
function to fail. You can encode like this (for UTF\-8):
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        use Encode qw(encode);
\&        $message = encode(\*(AqUTF\-8\*(Aq, $message);
.Ve
.PP
\fIget_legacy_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_legacy_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address_string = $object\->get_legacy_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns string containing Base58Check encoded public key hash (\f(CW\*(C`p2pkh\*(C'\fR address).
.PP
If the public key was obtained through BIP44 derivation scheme, this method
will check whether the purpose was \f(CW44\fR and raise an exception otherwise. If
you wish to generate this address anyway, call \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_compat_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_compat_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address_string = $object\->get_compat_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns string containing Base58Check encoded script hash containing a witness
program for compatibility purposes (\f(CWp2sh(p2wpkh)\fR address)
.PP
If the public key was obtained through BIP44 derivation scheme, this method
will check whether the purpose was \f(CW49\fR and raise an exception otherwise. If
you wish to generate this address anyway, call \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_segwit_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_segwit_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address_string = $object\->get_segwit_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a string containing Bech32 encoded witness version 0 program (\f(CW\*(C`p2wpkh\*(C'\fR
address)
.PP
If the public key was obtained through BIP44 derivation scheme, this method
will check whether the purpose was \f(CW84\fR and raise an exception otherwise. If
you wish to generate this address anyway, call \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_taproot_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_taproot_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address_string = $object\->get_taproot_address($script_tree = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Returns a string containing Bech32m encoded witness version 1 program (\f(CW\*(C`p2tr\*(C'\fR
address)
.PP
Optional \f(CW$script_tree\fR can be passed as Bitcoin::Crypto::Script::Tree
object. Passing this argument will generate an address that can be spent using
script path spend as well as key path spend. If this argument is not passed, an
unspendable script path will be used according to BIP341.
.PP
If the public key was obtained through BIP44 derivation scheme, this method
will check whether the purpose was \f(CW86\fR and raise an exception otherwise. If
you wish to generate this address anyway, call \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\fIget_address\fR
.IX Subsection "get_address"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $address_string = $object\->get_address()
.Ve
.PP
Returns a string containing the address. Tries to guess which address type is
most fitting:
.IP \(bu 4
If the key has a BIP44 purpose set, generates type of address which
matches the purpose
.IP \(bu 4
If the key doesn\*(Aqt have a purpose but the network supports segwit,
returns a taproot address (same as \f(CW\*(C`get_taproot_address\*(C'\fR, but does not accept
a script tree)
.IP \(bu 4
If the network doesn\*(Aqt support segwit, returns legacy address
.PP
\&\fBNOTE\fR: The rules this function uses to choose the address type \fBwill\fR
change when more up\-to\-date address types are implemented. Use
other address functions if this is not what you want.
